# Retail Analytics
This project focuses on enhancing customer experience by providing customers relevant recommendations on grocery store items that are most commonly bought based on either their purchase history, items in cart, or other associations, through a machine learning model that uses Association Rule Mining (an a priori algorithm)

# The Context
The goal of our analysis and report is to build personalized grocery baskets and an intelligent product recommendation system to improve the customer online experience which will help the "company" keep their existing customers but also conquer those who are still hesitating to join. In order to achieve that, our team would provide TNG Strategic Solutions and recommendations to help them optimize the sales of their grocery baskets, so client do not spend too much time online looking for specific items.

Our company is obsessed about providing their customers best experience possible and has asked us to improve the shopping experience of the customer by providing them with pre- grocery baskets for weekly groceries. Our target audience is the end customer of the website. With the dataset supplied, we can recommend them product(s) that the customer will most likely buy and add it to the basket. Basket will be customizable, allowing the customer to add/ edit/ delete the items. Initially, the baskets will be created with available purchase history and with time TNG will be able to accurately predict the weekly groceries by further capturing the purchase data of the customers.

<h3>5. MODELING, EVALUATION, AND DEPLOYMENT</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>5.1 The Goal of our Model</p>
</blockquote>
<p>When considering the type of data we have, our business problem, our
findings from data exploration, and the nature of our analytical work,
our team has decided to go with an a priori machine learning algorithm.
What this means is that our model will learn from customers patterns of
<strong>previously</strong> purchased products, and then apply that
learned knowledge to any customer profile. We chose this algorithm in
order to recommend to the customer <strong>the</strong> most precise and
relevant items that will either keep customer loyalty or add value to
their basket/online visit (or both!), which will be based on either
their current basket or their historic purchases, if they are a
recurring customer.</p>
<p>To perform our analyses and model evaluation, we will use the R
package called <em>arules</em>, which is specifically made for apriori
learning.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb2"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb2-1"><a href="#cb2-1" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">library</span>(arules)</span></code></pre></div>
<blockquote>
<p>5.2 The Theory behind the Algorithm</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This package uses the algorithm called <strong>Association Rule
Mining</strong> to draw insight from a given basket (ie transaction),
and developing <em>associations</em> between item sets, essentially
creating relationships between frequently bought items. There are
generally two steps behind the algorithm which is made up of 1.
Generation of the Frequent Itemset, and 2. Rule Generation.</p>
<p>Frequent Itemset Generation essentially creates a candidate list of
those items that qualify as frequent enough, by making an itemset
lattice. From this lattice there are various sets (ex. {Milk} as one
set, or {Milk, Eggs} as another, and {Milk, Bread, Butter} as another)
that have relations to one another. The apriori algorithm then helps
reduce the number of lattice relations by pruning certain sets and/or
supersets that are considered infrequent, thereby creating a candidate
list of only relevant item sets. This relevant list will help us
generate meaningful rule associations.</p>
<p>For more detailed information on the apriori algorithm please check
this documentation: <a href="https://dwgeek.com/mining-frequent-itemsets-apriori-algorithm.html/" class="uri">https://dwgeek.com/mining-frequent-itemsets-apriori-algorithm.html/</a></p>
<blockquote>
<p>5.3 Creating our Basket Transactions</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Before we begin association rule mining, we need to convert our
dataframe into basket format, meaning that all the items bought
together in one invoice (ie. order_id), must all be in the same row.
Currently our data has one item per row. Therefore, we will group our
data based on order_id. We will <em>also</em> group our data based on
user_id in order to see what the differences are between mining data
based on order transactions or mining data based on all of the users
transactions, since our objective is to cater our recommendations
towards our customers.</p>

<blockquote>
<p>5.4 Assessing and Developing our Association Rules</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Now we can finally apply our rule association algorithm to our
transaction data that we have just formatted. To get an initial sense of
what we will be looking for, we will first run our algorithm on the
order data with the default parameters.</p>

<p>Before going any further, we must explain some very key concepts in
terms of our performance metrics and what we are looking for. There are
three (3) key metrics that we need to consider for our data:
<em>Support</em>, <em>Confidence</em>, and <em>Lift</em>.</p>
<p><em>Support</em> refers to how many transactions support the given
condition. A high support means the condition occurs various times
throughout our matrix. A small support means the condition occurs very
few times, and thus not a very supported condition.</p>
<p><em>Confidence</em> refers to how certain a condition is. A
confidence of 1 means that 100% of customers who bought item 1, also
bought item 2. A confidence of 0.5 means 50% of customers who bought
item 1, bought item 2 (and thus the other 50% of customers who bought
item 1, did NOT buy item 2).</p>
<p>Lastly, <em>Lift</em> is how often the condition actually happens
compared to the expected chance for that condition to happen. In other
words, lift is the ratio of confidence to expected confidence. Lift is a
good rule of thumb that describes the strength of an association between
items, <em>however</em> it is also good to be wary that lift can be
inflated due to coincidences, therefore it is always good to look at
support and confidence just as much. Typically a lift of 1.0 means that
the rule/item set is occurring as expected.</p>

<p>Here we see that the default parameters have created rules that have
an average support of 0.001897, and average confidence of 0.9774, and an
average lift of 431.4. As we just mentioned, a lift of 1 means the rule
is behaving as expected. A lift of 2 means that the rule is occuring

lift of 431 is extremely high. Same for our average confidence of
0.9774, which is very high, but could be due to that we subsetted our
parameters to choose rules with only 80% (0.8) confidence or higher.</p>

<p>It is very interesting to note how vastly different the rules
generated are between the two datasets. The default rules produce
various associations related to toiletries (paper towel, toilet paper,
napkins), bread related purchases, and juices. The new order rules, with
a higher minimum support, produce associations such as milk and yogurt,
juice items, snacks, salads and dressing. Lastly, the rules based on
users transactions seem to be somewhat more refined as well as
diversified, with associations such as cheese and sandwiches and turkey,
vodka and an item called texas, bread and fibre, pasta and meat sauce,
vegetables and cheese.</p>
<p>as tempting as it may be</p>
<p>From the quick inspection into the rules, as well as the summary
statistics that we have observed, there seems to be varying results
based on if we perform our data mining on order transactions or on
users transaction. <em>Statistically</em> speaking, the order
transactions data seems to have better metrics in terms of lift, and
confidence, but this could be due to the fact that order transactions
has more random, one-off purchases that occur more than expected, which
is the cause for high lift. This can also be explained through the
<em>density</em> previously mentioned, where rules based on order has a
smaller density. Since user_rules have a higher density, it could
provide more meaningful results, especially seeing since our goal is to
provide our customers with <em>personalized</em> recommendations to
strengthen and maintain their loyalty. Also from our quick inspection,
we see that the associations that user_rules created seemed to be more
diversified than the order_rules.</p>
<p>As tempting as it may be to continue our analysis using order_rules
because it has higher lift and confidence values overall, we must
remember to take the lift metric with a grain of salt as the lift metric
could perform poorly when there is random noise. As mentioned by this
paper, lift has a strong tendency to produce the highest values for
rules which just pass the set minimum support threshold. (<a href="https://michael.hahsler.net/research/hyperConfidence_IDA2007/hyperConfidence.pdf" class="uri">https://michael.hahsler.net/research/hyperConfidence_IDA2007/hyperConfidence.pdf</a>)
This is theoretically true for the orders data since there are probably
many more one-off purchases that have no connection, whereas the users
data will have more meaningful itemset connections.</p>
<p>Not to mention, user_rules has many more rules (9319) than
order_rules which has a mere (70). Therefore, we will continue to refine
our model using the transactions based on user filtering.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>5.5 Refining Our Model</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Now that we have decided to use user_transactions as for our data
mining, we will further subset this dataset to users that have more than
5 orders (users that have ordered from us more than 5 times). We choose
5 seeing as once a customers shops at our store more than 5 times, we
would consider that as being a loyal customer. We do this in order to
get a better idea of our loyal customers shopping habits, since we want
to cater our recommendations towards these users.</p>
<p>We will perform the same steps we previously took in order to get the
rule associations for our loyal customers.</p>

<p>From this inspection, we see various reciprocal associations, where
there are various two-sided relationships. In other words, two items
listed as an association are listed again in the subsequent row except
their position is reversed (from lhs to rhs, and from rhs to lhs in the
next row). We can try to avoid this by further subsetting our results,
by removing rules that are subsets of larger rules.</p>
